Q: Given x(n), compute X(w)?
	Fourier Analysis:
		x(n)=\sigma(n) --> X(w)=1

		Notice that Fourier transform is linear.

		x(n)=\sum_(-inf)^(inf) x(k) \sigma(n-k)

		y(n) --FT-> Y(w)
		y(n-k) --FT-> Y(w)e^(-iwk)
		y(n-k) --FT-> 1/(2 pi) \integral_(-pi)^(pi) e^(-iwk) e^(iwn) dw

		So...
		X(w)=\sum_(-inf)^(inf) x(k)e^(-iwk)
		\sigma(n-k)--FT-->1e^(-iwk)

		In summary:
			x(n)=1/(2\pi) \integral_(-\pi)^(\pi) X(w) e^(iwn) dw (Synthesis)
			X(w)=\sum_(-\inf)^(\inf)x(k) e^(-iwk)

		x(n-k) --FT-->e^(-iwk) X(w)
		e^(iwn) x(n) --FT--> X(w-w_c)
